Trends and outcomes of mental health-related television news coverage in Australia, 2002-2012.

Science.gov (United States)

Goffman, Daniel; Clarke, Jane; Aitken, Zena; Clay-Williams, Robyn

2015-01-01

To examine long-term trends and content analysis of the ways mental illness-related television news reports portray (a) story topics, (b) people with mental illness, (c) treatments and response to psychiatric treatment. We collected television news broadcasts from the three major Australian networks for 2002-2012. The primary outcome data collected included the year and time of day broadcasts occurred, the type of news story and subjects covered, and the prominence of mental health themes in a news viewer attention framework. Multiway analyses of variance (MANOVA) assessed trends in the proportion of stories depicting people with mental illness and the top five treatments described in mental health-related stories over time.
